From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Sun, 21 Jun 2026 16:40:38 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] brush-core: add Shell::run_argv; run env/nice/... through it,
 drop the quoting
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Adds `Shell::run_argv(argv, params)`: runs an ALREADY-SPLIT argv as a simple
command through the shell's full dispatch (function → builtin → external) with
NO re-expansion — it feeds the argv straight to `execute_command` as literal
`CommandArg::String`s and waits the spawn result. A function/builtin runs
in-process against the given shell's logical state; an external is spawned
through the same (box-snooped) path as any other command; the returned exit
status and observable effects match running the command normally. The caller
picks the shell (a clone for subshell semantics, or self to persist effects).

The exec-wrappers (env/nice/setsid/nohup) now call `run_argv` instead of
round-tripping the residual `COMMAND [ARG]...` through `run_string` with every
piece force-single-quoted to survive a re-parse. Same semantics, no quoting
dance.

Verified via env/nice across all categories with observable equivalence to
external execution: in-process builtin dispatch (`env type type` →
"shell builtin", with no /usr/bin/type), a shell FUNCTION that exists only in
this shell (`env greet hello`), env propagation + exit code to an external
(`env FOO=bar sh -c …`; `exit 7` → $?==7), a shebang SCRIPT carrying env/cwd/
args/exit (`env -C dir FOO=zzz ./s.sh ARG` → exit 3), `-C` cwd to a builtin
(`env -C /tmp pwd`), and subshell isolation (FOO does not leak). 93 engine
tests still pass.

